# DRAFT FOR ANALYST REVIEW — CVE-2026-60002
#
# Vulnerability: OpenSSH < 10.4 use-after-free via host key change during
# key re-exchange (KEX). The server changes its host key mid-session during
# a renegotiation, triggering client-side memory corruption. Network-
# exploitable: AV:N/PR:N/UI:N, CVSS 7.7 HIGH [1]. Fixed in OpenSSH 10.4
# released 2026-07-06 [2][3].
#
# PoC status: No public PoC known — pattern inferred from the
# CVE/advisory description only.
#
# PCAP status: No packet-capture (PCAP) data source is available to this
# pipeline — this pattern is NOT verified against captured exploit traffic.
#
# Confidence: LOW.
#   The exploit requires two specific SSH message types to appear in rapid
#   succession within an established SSH session: an SSH2_MSG_KEXINIT (byte
#   0x14, decimal 20) initiating re-exchange, followed closely by an
#   SSH2_MSG_NEWKEYS (byte 0x15, decimal 21) — the combination is consistent
#   with a mid-session host key change during re-exchange. However, SSH
#   traffic is encrypted after the initial handshake; Suricata can only
#   observe plaintext framing (packet lengths, message type bytes) in the
#   unencrypted initial KEX phase. Triggering this bug during a *re*-exchange
#   (i.e. after the session is already encrypted) means the distinguishing
#   bytes may NOT be observable in cleartext. This rule targets the
#   unencrypted initial KEX window only and may miss in-session re-exchange
#   abuse entirely. Analyst must validate whether deployment environment
#   performs SSH decryption (e.g. via a TLS/SSH inspection proxy) for this
#   rule to have meaningful coverage of the actual exploit path. Do not
#   deploy in IPS/drop mode without PCAP-verified tuning.
#
# Detection rationale:
#   During the initial (cleartext) SSH handshake, SSH2_MSG_KEXINIT (0x14)
#   is sent by both sides. A rapid succession of KEXINIT messages from the
#   server side on an established connection — or an anomalously fast
#   NEWKEYS (0x15) immediately following a server-initiated KEXINIT — may
#   indicate an attempted mid-handshake host key substitution consistent
#   with the described trigger condition. The rule looks for the SSH
#   protocol banner followed by a server-side KEXINIT within the cleartext
#   window. The threshold is set conservatively to reduce false positives
#   from legitimate re-key events.
#
# Recommended analyst actions before deployment:
#   1. Confirm OpenSSH version scope in your environment (patch to >= 10.4).
#   2. Test against known-good SSH re-key traffic to assess false-positive
#      rate; legitimate periodic re-keying will produce the same bytes.
#   3. If SSH decryption is available, refine with post-handshake KEXINIT
#      byte matching.
#   4. Treat as a canary/alerting rule only — do NOT set to drop/reject
#      without validated PCAP evidence.

alert tcp $EXTERNAL_NET any -> $HOME_NET 22 (
  msg:"THREATFORGE CVE-2026-60002 OpenSSH use-after-free host key change during re-exchange attempt";
  flow:established,to_client;
  content:"SSH-2.0-"; depth:8; offset:0;
  content:"|00 00 00|"; within:20;
  content:"|14|"; within:6;
  threshold:type both, track by_src, count 3, seconds 30;
  reference:cve,2026-60002;
  metadata:mitre_technique_id T1190, is_kev false, status experimental;
  classtype:attempted-admin; sid:9000004; rev:1; )

